ce:section.ce:para:
The products of low-temperature (140–220 °C) hydrothermal process are mainly hydrochar and liquid-phase products and very low amounts of gas-phase products and bio-oil. The N distribution in hydrochar, liquid-phase products, gas and loss is shown in Fig. 1
                        . With increasing temperature from 140 °C to 220 °C (for 1 h), the yields of hydrochar-N decreased dramatically from 52.6 ± 1.5% to 9.1 ± 1.7%, while that of liquid-N increased significantly from 45.7 ± 1.8% to 89.7 ± 2.0%. As the reaction time was prolonged from 1 h to 4 h at 180 °C, the yield of hydrochar-N decreased from 27.6 ± 1.9% to 15.3 ± 1.6%, and that of liquid-N increased from 67.8 ± 1.6% to 82.7 ± 1.9%. Gas-N and loss were measured by weight difference and both did not show significant relevance towards the changes in temperature and reaction time. In the reaction temperature (140–220 °C) and time range (1–4 h) studied, the increase in temperature nearly doubled the amount of nitrogen in the liquid phase, leading to a sharp decline in the nitrogen content in hydrochar. The increase in temperature and reaction time promoted the conversion and migration of hydrochar-N to liquid-N, and the effect of temperature was more significant. Nitrogen migration occurred because the hydrochar was constantly broken down into small molecules and then dissolved into liquid phase with increasing reaction temperature and time. This finding is in good agreement with the change in hydrochar yield (Table 1
                        ).
